Source: picam-orchestrator
Section: video
Priority: optional
Maintainer: Jaco Hanekom <jhanekom@gmail.com>
Build-Depends: debhelper-compat (= 13),
               golang-go (>= 2:1.22~)
Standards-Version: 4.6.2
Rules-Requires-Root: no

Package: picam-orchestrator
Architecture: arm64
Depends: ${shlibs:Depends}, ${misc:Depends}, picam-raw, picam-hailo, aipicam-config
Description: MJPEG stream + camera control backend for picam-raw + picam-hailo (Go)
 Headless backend exposing Main / Lores live video as plain HTTP MJPEG
 (multipart/x-mixed-replace) at GET /stream/main.mjpeg and
 GET /stream/lores.mjpeg — directly usable as an <img src="..."> in a
 browser, no signaling handshake needed — plus a JSON status endpoint
 (/status.json), an on-the-fly OSD toggle (/osd), a per-resolution
 annotation toggle (/annotate), and a camera-switch proxy to picam-raw
 (/camera?id=N). No web interface of its own, and typically not talked
 to by a browser directly — picam-frontend is the normal client,
 relaying the MJPEG stream on to browsers, though nothing stops a
 browser from pointing straight at this process's stream URLs. Main and
 Lores are live feeds straight from picam-raw; either can be switched
 into a delayed+annotated mode that matches detections from
 picam-hailo by timestamp and draws bounding boxes onto the delayed
 frames. Also drives picam-recorder on detection activity and writes
 JSON event-log files alongside recordings. Event snapshot files saved
 to disk are plain JPEG.
 .
 This is a Go reimplementation of the original C++ picam-orchestrator's
 detection/recording/control logic, though the live-stream transport
 has since diverged from that original: it started as WebRTC/VP8, which
 was replaced with MJPEG-over-HTTP because VP8 has no hardware encode
 path on any Raspberry Pi and software VP8 encoding was overloading the
 CPU — JPEG has no inter-frame prediction, so it's inherently far
 cheaper even in pure software. Pure Go, no cgo dependency.
 .
 Install picam-frontend on one machine to get a browser UI that can
 view, switch cameras, and toggle the OSD across multiple
 picam-orchestrator backends (e.g. several Pis) from one page.
 .
 Config: /etc/picam-orchestrator/config.ini
